Notes:

--- What is the class of imoto/izimoto, and what's up with those
prefixes?
--- What is the actual distribution of -ya- (present tense) and
when can/must it be left out?

# 1. Dogs sleep
izin-ja zi-ya-lal-a
c10-dog c10-sleep-FV

# 2. Dogs chase cars
izin-ja zi-zi-xosh-a izi-moto
c10-dog c10-c10-chase-FV c10-car

izin-ja zi-ya-zi-xosh-a izi-moto
c10-dog c10-pres-c10-chase-FV c10-car

# 3. They chase them.
zi-ya-zi-xosh-a
c10-pres-c10-chase-FV

# 4. These dogs sleep.
izin-ja lezi zi-ya-lal-a
c10-dog these c10-pres-sleep-FV

# 5. Dogs eat.
izin-ja zi-ya-dl-a
c10-dog c10-pres-eat-FV

# 6. I can eat glass.
ngi-nga-dl-a in-gilazi
1sg-can-eat-FV c9-glass

# 7. It doesn't hurt me.
a-ku-ya-ngi-limaz-a

# 8. The dogs chase cars  (not different from #2)
izin-ja zi-ya-zi-xosh-a izi-moto
izin-ja zi-zi-xosh-a izi-moto

# 9. I think that you know that dogs chase cars.

ngi-ya-cabang-a ukuba u-ya-az-a ukuba izin-ja zi-ya-zi-xosh-a izi-moto

# 10. I ask whether you know that dogs chase cars.

ngi-ya-zibuz-a ukuba u-ya-az-a ukuba izin-ja zi-ya-zi-xosh-a izi-moto

# 11. Cats and dogs chase cars.  # Seems to be a WITH coordination language
ama-kati na-izin-ja  a-ya-zi-xosh-a izi-moto
c6-cat   with-c10-dog c6-pres-c10-chase-FV ?-car

# 12. Dogs chase cars and cats chase dogs.
izin-ja zi-ya-zi-xosh-e izi-moto ama-kati a-ya-zi-xosh-a izin-ja

# 13. Cats chase dogs and sleep.
ama-kati a-ya-zi-xosh-e izin-ja a-ya-lal-a.

# 14. Do cats chase dogs?

ama-kati a-ya-zi-xosh-a izin-ja na
c6-cat   c6-FUT-c10-chase-FV c10-dog QP

# 15. Chase the dog!

xosh-a-ni izin-ja

# 16. Hungry dogs eat.  # No lexical adjective for hungry, would
			# need a relative clause based on the verb -labile.

izin-ja ezi-lambile-yo zi-ya-dl-a
c10-dog c10-hungry-rel c10-fut-eat-FV

# 17. Hungry dogs eat quickly. 

izin-ja ezi-lambile-yo zi-ya-dl-a ngokushesha
